Rating: 4
The first time I made it was for Christmas and got overwhelming raves. The second time, I just threw it together for a weeknight dinner. Seriously. It's that easy and that worth it. In making it twice, I've done it two different ways just to kind of experiment (somewhat out of necessity). Once using yukon gold and two different kinds of sweet potatoes, following the rest of the recipe. And now a second time using only yukon golds and dried sage (ran out of fresh). I think I overdid it with the dried sage (I was in a hurry and didn't calculate properly the difference between dried v. fresh), but I really preferred the straight yukon gold dish. I liked not having to bother peeling all those potatoes. :) I have a mandoline, but have no clue where it is. I just put everything through my food processor and it was fine. This is definitely now on my list of go to recipes. I look forward to trying different cheeses and potatoes. I think it might also be good with an onion and/or Granny Smith apple thrown in for interest.

